T1  - Using Laboratory Brand Preference Scales to Predict Consumer Brand Purchases
AU  - Pessemier, Edgar
AU  - Burger, Philip
AU  - Teach, Richard
AU  - Tigert, Douglas
Y1  - 1971/02/01
PY  - 1971
DA  - 1971/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.17.6.B371
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.17.6.B371
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - B-371
EP  - B-385
VL  - 17
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Laboratory measures of brand preferences and survey measures of demographic, media exposure, attitudinal, activity and opinion characteristics of individual consumers have been combined to predict brand purchases in the market. Brands in the tooth paste, liquid household cleaner and cake mix product categories were employed in a set of laboratory experiments. Preference scales derived from the experiments are used in three separate models to predict the subject's purchases recorded in seven months of diary data. The behavioral implications and predictive power of the models are interesting from both theoretical and applied points of view.
